even if you've got $0 in the bank.

41
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:28,700
If you don't know your freedom figure,

42
00:01:28,700 --> 00:01:31,880
then it's a bit like being
blindfolded in a running race.

43
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:33,430
You can't see where you're going.

44
00:01:33,430 --> 00:01:35,650
So you may end up putting all your efforts

45
00:01:35,650 --> 00:01:38,250
in going in the wrong
direction or even tripping up

46
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:39,830
and falling flat on your face.

47
00:01:39,830 --> 00:01:41,980
The reality is there are
three types of people

48
00:01:41,980 --> 00:01:45,270
in this world. There are
doers, dreamers, and drifters,

49
00:01:45,270 --> 00:01:47,210
otherwise known as the three Ds.

50
00:01:47,210 --> 00:01:48,043
Actually thinking about it,

51
00:01:48,043 --> 00:01:50,549
when I was at school, they
gave me a cap with D on it.

52
00:01:50,549 --> 00:01:52,700
They must have known I was a doer.

53
00:01:52,700 --> 00:01:55,440
So let's start off with
drifters. They go through life,

54
00:01:55,440 --> 00:01:59,140
living paycheck to paycheck,
without any financial aims,

55
00:01:59,140 --> 00:02:00,560
they don't really see the point

56
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:02,070
of saving or investing money

57
00:02:02,070 --> 00:02:03,295
as retirement feels like it's

58
00:02:03,295 --> 00:02:06,330
not something a young person
needs to be thinking about.

59
00:02:06,330 --> 00:02:08,270
Dreamers do have financial goals,

60
00:02:08,270 --> 00:02:09,796
but they don't have any plans in place

61
00:02:09,796 --> 00:02:11,530
to actually achieve them.

62
00:02:11,530 --> 00:02:14,000
So they will forever just stay dreams.

63
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,520
And finally, doers. They
have financial goals,

64
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:18,900
but most importantly,
have a plan to reach them.

65
00:02:18,900 --> 00:02:21,310
And that's where your
freedom figure comes in.

66
00:02:21,310 --> 00:02:23,090
This is a very individual thing

67
00:02:23,090 --> 00:02:24,540
and it all depends on how much

68
00:02:24,540 --> 00:02:28,030
you want to pay yourself
each year when you retire.

69
00:02:28,030 --> 00:02:29,980
There's actually a great
way to figure this out.

70
00:02:29,980 --> 00:02:31,953
And it's called the times
25 rule. So let's firstly,

71
00:02:31,953 --> 00:02:36,720
assume you want to make $50,000
per year without working.

72
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:41,090
Secondly, we would need
to multiply 50,000 by 25,

73
00:02:41,090 --> 00:02:43,830
which gives us 1.25 million dollars.

74
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:46,970
The idea is that you're able
to withdraw 4% of this per year

75
00:02:46,970 --> 00:02:48,680
without ever running out of money.

76
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:53,443
You guessed it, 4% of
$1.25 million is $50,000.

77
00:02:53,443 --> 00:02:55,890
1.25 million dollars,

78
00:02:55,890 --> 00:02:58,100
how am I ever going to
get that in seven years?

79
00:02:58,100 --> 00:02:59,520
This video's a lie!

80
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:01,090
I know this may sound tough,

81
00:03:01,090 --> 00:03:04,581
especially if you're starting
from $0, but it is possible.

82
00:03:04,581 --> 00:03:06,356
No one said it's going to be easy,

83
00:03:06,356 --> 00:03:09,030
but with the right
approach, it can be done.

84
00:03:09,030 --> 00:03:11,330
I mean, if I can do it, then so can you.

85
00:03:11,330 --> 00:03:13,167
In the early stages of
your retirement plan,

86
00:03:13,167 --> 00:03:15,524
the way you think about money is crucial.

87
00:03:15,524 --> 00:03:19,230
It's all about getting the
right mindset in place.

88
00:03:19,230 --> 00:03:23,030
The key is to prioritize
building wealth over cashflow.

89
00:03:23,030 --> 00:03:24,229
This is because building wealth,

90
00:03:24,229 --> 00:03:27,090
it's about locking your
money away in assets

91
00:03:27,090 --> 00:03:28,770
that increase in value.

92
00:03:28,770 --> 00:03:30,596
Whereas cashflow gives you more money

93
00:03:30,596 --> 00:03:33,308
flowing into your pocket.
Now this may sound great,

94
00:03:33,308 --> 00:03:35,520
but it can lead to a variety of problems,

95
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:38,960
such as lifestyle inflation
and sky high taxes.

96
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:42,194
Cash flow is extremely important,
but more so later in life,

97
00:03:42,194 --> 00:03:43,870
once you start to unwind.

98
00:03:43,870 --> 00:03:46,240
This is why whenever I
made some extra cash,

99
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:47,073
when I was younger,

100
00:03:47,073 --> 00:03:49,560
I made sure to reinvest
the majority of it.

101
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:50,530
Of course, I get it.

102
00:03:50,530 --> 00:03:52,160
Sometimes it can feel really nice

103
00:03:52,160 --> 00:03:55,033
to secure some profit and lock
it away in your bank account.

104
00:03:55,033 --> 00:03:57,470
It can give you a false sense of security

105
00:03:57,470 --> 00:03:59,930
knowing you've got all your
money sat in your account

106
00:03:59,930 --> 00:04:01,060
for whenever you need it.

107
00:04:01,060 --> 00:04:03,310
But the reality is you often
don't need as much money

108
00:04:03,310 --> 00:04:04,143
as you think.

109
00:04:04,143 --> 00:04:06,300
Forming a habit of in your cashflow

110
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:09,050
is absolutely essential when
it comes to building wealth,

111
00:04:09,050 --> 00:04:12,190
as fast as possible and
hitting your freedom figure.

112
00:04:12,190 --> 00:04:13,993
Phase two is laying the foundations.

113
00:04:13,993 --> 00:04:16,105
This is kind of like building a house.

114
00:04:16,105 --> 00:04:18,181
You need to lay a solid foundation

115
00:04:18,181 --> 00:04:20,340
to ensure your house doesn't crumble

116
00:04:20,340 --> 00:04:22,070
at the first sign of an earthquake.

117
00:04:22,070 --> 00:04:22,903
Unfortunately,

118
00:04:22,903 --> 00:04:26,083
70% of millennials now
live paycheck to paycheck,

119
00:04:26,083 --> 00:04:27,919
which means they're building their lives

120
00:04:27,919 --> 00:04:29,577
on an unstable base.

121
00:04:29,577 --> 00:04:32,010
Just like building a house on quicksand.

122
00:04:32,010 --> 00:04:33,470
If you find that unbelievable

123
00:04:33,470 --> 00:04:35,120
then this is even more shocking.

124
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:37,738
40% of Americans with an income greater

125
00:04:37,738 --> 00:04:40,140
than a hundred thousand dollars a year

126
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:42,860
are still living paycheck to paycheck.

127
00:04:42,860 --> 00:04:44,560
This just goes to show how important

128
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:46,190
laying the foundations are.

129
00:04:46,190 --> 00:04:47,603
And even though it may seem simple,

130
00:04:47,603 --> 00:04:50,330
many people are failing at this phase.

131
00:04:50,330 --> 00:04:51,642
There are four stages I considered

132
00:04:51,642 --> 00:04:54,142
when I was in this phase
during my early twenties.

133
00:04:54,142 --> 00:04:57,153
The first stage is paying
off high interest debt.

134
00:04:57,153 --> 00:04:58,840
It's crucial to pay this off

135
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:01,440
before you even consider
investing in your money,

136
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:03,830
as high interest debt is holding you back,

137
00:05:03,830 --> 00:05:04,663
but saying this,

138
00:05:04,663 --> 00:05:06,930
it is very important to
understand the difference

139
00:05:06,930 --> 00:05:09,230
between good debt and bad debt.

140
00:05:09,230 --> 00:05:12,250
Good debt is anything low
interest that makes you money.

141
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:14,572
For example, the mortgage
on a rental property

142
00:05:14,572 --> 00:05:17,220
or low interest finance on a laptop

143
00:05:17,220 --> 00:05:18,588
to build an online business.

144
00:05:18,588 --> 00:05:20,860
Bad debt is high interest debt

145
00:05:20,860 --> 00:05:22,450
that doesn't make you any money.

146
00:05:22,450 --> 00:05:24,350
For example, shopping for clothes

147
00:05:24,350 --> 00:05:27,050
on buy it now later credit card debt,

148
00:05:27,050 --> 00:05:28,970
or even a typical bank loan.

149
00:05:28,970 --> 00:05:31,930
All of this debt needs paying
off as soon as possible.

150
00:05:31,930 --> 00:05:34,080
I was in quite a lot
of debt when I was 18.

151
00:05:34,080 --> 00:05:35,210
And in order to get out of it,

152
00:05:35,210 --> 00:05:37,810
I used the debt avalanche method,

153
00:05:37,810 --> 00:05:39,719
which involves making the minimum payments

154
00:05:39,719 --> 00:05:41,900
on all my high interest debt.

155
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:44,640
Then I used any extra
money to pay off the debt

156
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:47,010
with the highest interest rate first,

157
00:05:47,010 --> 00:05:50,180
which was my store credit card at 32%.

158
00:05:50,180 --> 00:05:53,810
Crazy, I know. Signing up
for that was a huge mistake,

159
00:05:53,810 --> 00:05:56,234
which I've talked about
in some of my past videos.

160
00:05:56,234 --> 00:05:58,540
I then worked my way through the bad debt

161
00:05:58,540 --> 00:06:00,140
with the lowest interest rate,

162
00:06:00,140 --> 00:06:03,130
which was my car loan at
around 15% of the time.

163
00:06:03,130 --> 00:06:06,360
Within a year, I'd managed
to get everything paid off.

164
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:09,340
The big lesson here is you
can't invest to build wealth

165
00:06:09,340 --> 00:06:11,490
when being weighed down by bad debt.

166
00:06:11,490 --> 00:06:14,460
Stage two is putting
aside an emergency fund.

167
00:06:14,460 --> 00:06:16,125
This is essential for your foundations

168
00:06:16,125 --> 00:06:19,520
because if you start investing
without an emergency fund,

169
00:06:19,520 --> 00:06:21,461
you might find a few months down the line,

170
00:06:21,461 --> 00:06:23,210
you get into a spot of bother

171
00:06:23,210 --> 00:06:26,430
with an unexpected expense
and no cash to pay for it.

172
00:06:26,430 --> 00:06:28,680
You will then have to
pull your investments out

173
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,070
to cover the expense,

174
00:06:30,070 --> 00:06:32,300
and then you'll miss out
on the potential profits.

175
00:06:32,300 --> 00:06:35,030
Stage three is building
a great credit score.

176
00:06:35,030 --> 00:06:37,180
A credit score is a bit like your resume.

177
00:06:37,180 --> 00:06:39,794
It follows you around in
life, is regularly updated,

178
00:06:39,794 --> 00:06:41,241
and it helps lenders decide

179
00:06:41,241 --> 00:06:43,220
whether you're a worthy borrower.

180
00:06:43,220 --> 00:06:45,550
Having a good credit score
is especially important

181
00:06:45,550 --> 00:06:48,130
if you ever want to get a loan
in the future, for example,

182
00:06:48,130 --> 00:06:49,750
to buy your dream house.

183
00:06:49,750 --> 00:06:51,680
You just never know when
you're going to need it.

184
00:06:51,680 --> 00:06:54,050
I should have actually started
building my credit score

185
00:06:54,050 --> 00:06:57,136
a lot sooner than I did because
it's so easy to get started.

186
00:06:57,136 --> 00:07:00,040
All you need to do, as soon as you turn 18

187
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,800
is get yourself a credit card.

188
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:04,080
Start putting in a few
little expenses on it

189
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:06,730
like gas and pay that baby off in full

190
00:07:06,730 --> 00:07:08,260
at the end of each and every month.

191
00:07:08,260 --> 00:07:09,870
This way you pay no interest

192
00:07:09,870 --> 00:07:12,650
and prove to the lenders that
you're a reliable borrower.

193
00:07:12,650 --> 00:07:15,990
Stage four is reducing your tax liability.

194
00:07:15,990 --> 00:07:17,845
Every dollar you earn has hidden costs.

195
00:07:17,845 --> 00:07:19,770
Of all the expenses, however,

196
00:07:19,770 --> 00:07:21,330
taxes can sting the most

197
00:07:21,330 --> 00:07:23,670
and take the biggest
bite out of your money.

198
00:07:23,670 --> 00:07:25,310
No one likes the tax man.

199
00:07:25,310 --> 00:07:27,446
The good news is that
tax efficient accounts

200
00:07:27,446 --> 00:07:30,080
can minimize how much tax you have to pay

201
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:31,980
and maximize your savings.

202
00:07:31,980 --> 00:07:33,010
In my early twenties,

203
00:07:33,010 --> 00:07:35,900
my income was really starting
to get eaten up by taxes.

204
00:07:35,900 --> 00:07:37,830
So I started looking for the best ways

205
00:07:37,830 --> 00:07:39,720
to save as much as possible.

206
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:42,215
I then discovered if I opened
up a retirement account,

207
00:07:42,215 --> 00:07:45,730
the I can save money I hadn't paid tax on.

208
00:07:45,730 --> 00:07:49,930
This is known as a 401k in
the USA and a SIPP in the UK.

209
00:07:49,930 --> 00:07:52,290
Of course I will eventually
have to pay tax on this,

210
00:07:52,290 --> 00:07:53,162
but as I'll be older,

211
00:07:53,162 --> 00:07:55,510
I'll be in a much lower tax bracket

212
00:07:55,510 --> 00:07:56,630
because I'll be earning less.

213
00:07:56,630 --> 00:07:58,980
So hence, I should save
quite a lot of money.

214
00:07:58,980 --> 00:08:01,950
But I didn't stop there.
I opened another account,

215
00:08:01,950 --> 00:08:04,840
that allowed me to save
money that I'd pay tax on,

216
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:05,870
but in the future,

217
00:08:05,870 --> 00:08:08,600
I wouldn't have to pay
tax on my capital gains.

218
00:08:08,600 --> 00:08:12,030
Or in other words, all the
money that the money generated.

219
00:08:12,030 --> 00:08:16,640
This is called a Roth IRA in
the USA and an ISA in the UK.

220
00:08:16,640 --> 00:08:18,230
I firmly believe that everyone

221
00:08:18,230 --> 00:08:21,250
should set up both of these
accounts as soon as possible,

222
00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:24,190
as I know it really reduced my tax burden.

223
00:08:24,190 --> 00:08:26,620
So once you've built up
these solid foundations,

224
00:08:26,620 --> 00:08:28,500
it's time to start expanding.

225
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:31,032
Phase three is building
multiple income streams.

226
00:08:31,032 --> 00:08:33,170
I like to think about it like this.

227
00:08:33,170 --> 00:08:34,657
Imagine Spiderman is you.

228
00:08:34,657 --> 00:08:36,410
The platform is your life,

229
00:08:36,410 --> 00:08:38,300
and the skittle is your everyday job.

230
00:08:38,300 --> 00:08:40,433
If you get fired, guess what's happening.

231
00:08:42,090 --> 00:08:42,930
Now, imagine this.

232
00:08:42,930 --> 00:08:45,367
Spiderman is you, the
platform's your life.

233
00:08:45,367 --> 00:08:48,305
But now, you have multiple income streams.

234
00:08:48,305 --> 00:08:50,810
The stock market could crash.

235
00:08:50,810 --> 00:08:54,740
You could lose your job, or
your side hustle could fail,

236
00:08:54,740 --> 00:08:57,550
but your life is supported
by your other income streams.

237
00:08:57,550 --> 00:09:00,190
This makes it very hard
for someone or something

238
00:09:00,190 --> 00:09:02,900
to come along and strike you out.

239
00:09:02,900 --> 00:09:05,800
A secured job is nowhere
near as common as it once was

240
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:09,200
with the average person now
working 12 jobs in a lifetime.

241
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:11,610
There isn't one perfect
solution for everyone,

242
00:09:11,610 --> 00:09:13,850
but something that has
worked for me over the years

243
00:09:13,850 --> 00:09:16,410
is to pick side hustles
that take advantage

244
00:09:16,410 --> 00:09:18,250
of my existing skills.

245
00:09:18,250 --> 00:09:20,660
So I don't have to learn
something completely new.

246
00:09:20,660 --> 00:09:22,230
This will often end up being something

247
00:09:22,230 --> 00:09:24,800
you're passionate about
as you develop the skills

248
00:09:24,800 --> 00:09:25,990
without even knowing it.

249
00:09:25,990 --> 00:09:28,570
Sometimes we can lean towards
what will pay the most.

250
00:09:28,570 --> 00:09:30,600
But when looking to
build long-term wealth,

251
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:32,219
sustainability is important.

252
00:09:32,219 --> 00:09:34,380
So when waking up every morning,

253
00:09:34,380 --> 00:09:37,930
being passionate about your
line of work is a great idea.

254
00:09:37,930 --> 00:09:40,370
As Richard Branson once
told me over lunch,

